Now I have a complete picture of the codebase. Let me plan the migration:

## Current Pages Router Structure:
- `pages/_app.js` - Custom App with AppProvider, global layout (header, footer)
- `pages/_document.js` - Custom Document (HTML structure, fonts, meta)
- `pages/_error.js` - Custom error page with `getInitialProps`
- `pages/404.js` - Custom 404 page
- `pages/index.js` - Home page with `getServerSideProps`
- `pages/blog/index.js` - Blog index with `getStaticProps` + ISR
- `pages/blog/[id].js` - Blog post with `getStaticPaths` + `getStaticProps` + ISR
- `pages/api/posts/index.js` - API route (GET all, POST)
- `pages/api/posts/[id].js` - API route (GET one, PUT, DELETE)
- `components/AppProvider.js` - Context provider
- `styles/globals.css` - Global styles

## App Router Migration Plan:

### 1. Layout (replaces `_app.js` + `_document.js`)
- `app/layout.tsx` — Root layout wrapping everything in AppProvider, includes header/footer
- Move the global layout from `_app.js` here
- No need for `_document.js` — App Router uses `layout.tsx` with proper metadata API

### 2. Not-found (replaces `404.js`)
- `app/not-found.tsx` — Uses the `notFound` function from `next/navigation` instead of `useRouter`

### 3. Error (replaces `_error.js`)
- `app/error.tsx` — App Router's error boundary pattern (`use client`, `error` and `reset` props)

### 4. Home page (replaces `pages/index.js`)
- `app/page.tsx` — Replace `getServerSideProps` with `fetch` in an async Server Component

### 5. Blog index (replaces `pages/blog/index.js`)
- `app/blog/page.tsx` — Replace `getStaticProps` with a direct async fetch, use `revalidate` in fetch options

### 6. Blog post by ID (replaces `pages/blog/[id].js`)
- `app/blog/[id]/page.tsx` — Replace `getStaticPaths` with `generateStaticParams`, `getStaticProps` with async component fetch + `revalidate`

### 7. API routes (replace `pages/api/posts/index.js` and `[id].js`)
- `app/api/posts/route.ts` — Handle GET and POST
- `app/api/posts/[id]/route.ts` — Handle GET, PUT, DELETE

### Key App Router patterns:
- `useRouter` from `next/router` → `useRouter` from `next/navigation` (for client components)
- Navigation: `router.push()` → `useRouter().push()` from `next/navigation`
- `Head` from `next/head` → `metadata` export or `next/head` still works
- No more `getServerSideProps`, `getStaticProps`, `getStaticPaths` — just fetch directly in components
- `generateStaticParams` replaces `getStaticPaths`
- API routes use the Web `Request`/`Response` API instead of `req`/`res`
- `next/document` no longer used — layout handles HTML structure via `html` and `body` props
- Convert `.js` files to `.tsx`/`.ts` with proper types

Let me do this migration now. I'll create tasks for tracking and then proceed.

Let me plan all the files I need to create:

**New App Router files:**
1. `app/layout.tsx` — Root layout (replaces _app.js and _document.js)
2. `app/page.tsx` — Home page (replaces pages/index.js)
3. `app/not-found.tsx` — 404 page (replaces pages/404.js)
4. `app/error.tsx` — Error boundary (replaces _error.js, uses App Router pattern)
5. `app/blog/page.tsx` — Blog listing (replaces pages/blog/index.js)
6. `app/blog/[id]/page.tsx` — Blog post (replaces pages/blog/[id].js)
7. `app/api/posts/route.ts` — API route (replaces pages/api/posts/index.js)
8. `app/api/posts/[id]/route.ts` — API route (replaces pages/api/posts/[id].js)

Then I need to:
- Remove the pages directory
- Update tsconfig.json if needed
- Convert AppProvider to TypeScript
- Convert globals.css (already fine, just import it)

Let me think about the types needed:

For blog posts and comments from JSONPlaceholder:
```typescript
interface Post {
  userId: number;
  id: number;
  title: string;
  body: string;
}

interface Comment {
  postId: number;
  id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
  body: string;
}
```

For the API routes, I need:
```typescript
interface ApiPost {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  content: string;
  createdAt?: string;
  updatedAt?: string;
}
```

For App Router, the `error.tsx` page needs to be a client component and receives `error` and `reset` props.

Let me think about the `useRouter` replacement:
- Server components: `redirect` from `next/navigation`
- Client components: `useRouter` from `next/navigation` (different from `next/router`!)

For the links, I should use `next/link` Link component where possible instead of `router.push`.

For the `router.back()` on the blog post page, in App Router I can use `useRouter().back()` from `next/navigation` but it needs to be in a client component. Or I can use `next/link` with a button or use `window.history.back()`. Let me use `useRouter` from `next/navigation` with `"use client"`.

Wait, let me think about which pages need to be client components vs server components:

1. **layout.tsx** - Can be a server component. But `AppProvider` uses `useState` for theme, so I need to handle this. In App Router, context providers need to be in a client component wrapper. I'll create a separate client component for the provider wrapper.

2. **page.tsx (home)** - Can be a server component since `router.push` used in the button can be replaced with a `Link` component.

3. **not-found.tsx** - Needs `useRouter` from `next/navigation` for the button click to navigate home. So this needs `"use client"`.

4. **error.tsx** - Must be a client component by definition.

5. **blog/page.tsx** - Can be a server component. Replace `router.push` with `Link`.

6. **blog/[id]/page.tsx** - Can mostly be a server component. The `router.isFallback` pattern is replaced by just checking if the params exist in App Router (since the component receives params directly). The `router.back()` part would need a client component, but I can extract that into a separate client component or use `Link`.

Actually, let me re-think. In App Router with dynamic params:

```typescript
// app/blog/[id]/page.tsx
export default async function BlogPost({ params }: { params: { id: string } }) {
  // params.id is directly available
  // No need for router.isFallback since the page either exists or uses notFound
}
```

For the "back" button, I can make a small client component `BackButton` or use a Link.

Let me also think about `generateMetadata` for SEO:

```typescript
// app/blog/[id]/page.tsx
export async function generateMetadata({ params }: { params: { id: string } }): Promise<Metadata> {
  const post = await fetch(`https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/${params.id}`).then(res => res.json());
  return {
    title: `${post.title} - My Blog`,
    description: post.body.substring(0, 160),
    openGraph: { title: post.title, description: post.body.substring(0, 160) },
  };
}
```

For `generateStaticParams`:
```typescript
export async function generateStaticParams() {
  const posts = await fetch('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts').then(res => res.json());
  return posts.slice(0, 10).map((post: Post) => ({ id: post.id.toString() }));
}
```

For ISR (revalidate), in App Router I use:
```typescript
fetch(url, { next: { revalidate: 300 } })
```

Or at the page level with `export const revalidate = 300;`

OK let me finalize the plan and start creating files.

For `AppProvider`, I should convert it to TypeScript and make it a client component. Since it uses `useState` and `createContext`, it needs `"use client"`.

For the layout, I need the client component wrapper pattern:

```tsx
// app/providers.tsx - client component
'use client';
import { AppProvider } from '@/components/AppProvider';

export default function Providers({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return <AppProvider>{children}</AppProvider>;
}
```

Then `app/layout.tsx` wraps content with `<Providers>`.

Let me also consider the metadata API for the root layout:

```tsx
import type { Metadata } from 'next';

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: {
    default: 'My Blog',
    template: '%s - My Blog',
  },
  description: 'A complex blog application',
  icons: { icon: '/favicon.ico' },
};
```

The fonts preconnect can be handled in layout too.

Now, for the `_document.js` replacement - the font preconnect links can be added to the root layout's `<head>` via the metadata API or directly in layout.tsx.

Actually, in App Router, you can't add `<link>` tags directly in layout.tsx without using the metadata API or a special approach. The metadata API supports `other` for arbitrary tags. Let me check...

Actually, you can use:
```tsx
export const metadata: Metadata = {
  other: {
    'link:preconnect': ['https://fonts.googleapis.com'],
  }
};
```

Hmm, that's not quite right. In Next.js App Router, the way to add link tags is:

1. Through `metadata`:
```tsx
export const metadata: Metadata = {
  icons: { ... },
  other: {
    'link': [
      { rel: 'preconnect', href: 'https://fonts.googleapis.com' },
    ]
  }
};
```

Actually, the simplest approach is just to add it in the layout:
```tsx
<html>
  <head>
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com" />
    <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Inter:wght@400;500;600&display=swap" rel="stylesheet" />
  </head>
  <body>
    ...
  </body>
</html>
```

But actually, in App Router, the `head` tag inside layout doesn't directly support link tags that way. The proper approach uses `metadata` for this. Let me use:

```tsx
import type { Metadata } from 'next';

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: { default: 'My Blog', template: '%s - My Blog' },
  description: 'A complex blog application',
  icons: { icon: '/favicon.ico' },
  other: {
    'link': [
      'rel=preconnect https://fonts.googleapis.com',
    ],
  },
};
```

Actually, looking at the metadata API more carefully, fonts can be imported via CSS or via `next/font`. Since the original code uses a `<link>` for Inter font, I could either:

1. Use `next/font/google` (the modern App Router approach)
2. Keep the link tags in the HTML using a different approach

Let me use `next/font/google` since that's the proper App Router pattern:

```tsx
import { Inter } from 'next/font/google';

const inter = Inter({ subsets: ['latin'], display: 'swap' });
```

Then apply it to the body. This would replace both the preconnect and the stylesheet link.

OK, I think I have a clear plan. Let me now create all the files.

Let me update tasks and start implementing.

Actually wait, before I start creating all the files, let me think about `components/AppProvider.js`. I need to convert it to TypeScript and add `'use client'` directive.

Let me now create all files in one go:

1. `app/layout.tsx` 
2. `app/page.tsx`
3. `app/not-found.tsx`
4. `app/error.tsx`
5. `app/blog/page.tsx`
6. `app/blog/[id]/page.tsx`
7. `app/api/posts/route.ts`
8. `app/api/posts/[id]/route.ts`

And update:
9. `components/AppProvider.tsx` (rename from `.js`, add types + `'use client'`)

Then delete:
- `pages/` directory
- Old .js files

Let me also think about the `app/error.tsx` file. In App Router, the error boundary:
- Must be a client component (`'use client'`)
- Receives `error` and `reset` props
- `error` has `message` and `digest` properties (and `statusCode` in Next.js 13+ I think, but not sure)

Actually, for App Router error boundary:
```tsx
'use client';

export default function Error({ error, reset }: { error: Error & { digest?: string }; reset: () => void }) {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Something went wrong!</h1>
      <button onClick={reset}>Try again</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

The status code is typically determined by Next.js automatically. `error` has `.message` and `.digest`.

For the `not-found.tsx`, I can use `useRouter` from `next/navigation`:

```tsx
'use client';

import { useRouter } from 'next/navigation';
import Link from 'next/link';

export default function NotFound() {
  const router = useRouter();

  return (
    <div className="error-page">
      <h1>404 - Page Not Found</h1>
      <p>The page you're looking for doesn't exist.</p>
      <button onClick={() => router.push('/')}>Go Back Home</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

For the home page (server component), I'll use `fetch` directly and use `Link` component:

```tsx
import Link from 'next/link';
import type { Metadata } from 'next';

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: 'Home',
  description: 'Welcome to my blog homepage',
  openGraph: { title: 'Home - My Blog' },
};

interface Post {
  userId: number;
  id: number;
  title: string;
  body: string;
}

export default async function HomePage() {
  const posts: Post[] = await fetch(
    'https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts?_limit=5',
    { cache: 'no-store' }
  ).then(res => res.json());

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Welcome to My Blog</h1>
      <p>Server-side rendered at: {new Date().toISOString()}</p>

      <h2>Recent Posts</h2>
      <ul>
        {posts.map(post => (
          <li key={post.id}>
            <Link href={`/blog/${post.id}`}>{post.title}</Link>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>

      <Link href="/blog">
        <button>View All Posts</button>
      </Link>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Wait, but the original page had `userAgent` from the request headers. In App Router server components, I can get headers from `next/headers`:

```tsx
import { headers } from 'next/headers';

export default async function HomePage() {
  const headersList = await headers();
  const userAgent = headersList.get('user-agent') || '';
  // ...
}
```

Actually, in Next.js 16 (canary), `headers()` might be sync or async. Let me check the pattern.

In recent versions of Next.js (15+), `headers()` is async. But since they're using Next.js 16.2.0-canary.41, it likely follows the 15+ patterns:

```tsx
const headersList = await headers();
